## LLM-generating cron: real-gen vs silent dry-run (gotcha + technique, 2026-06-05)

**Recurring trap:** any cron that needs an LLM to WRITE code (mutation rounds, candidate gen) will SILENTLY fall back to `--dry-run` and only ever produce synthetic REJECTs if it tries to call `run_one_round()` inside a `python3 -c` subprocess. Reason: pure Python can't reach the `sessions_spawn` *tool* → `_default_spawn_fn` raises NotImplementedError by design → dry-run fallback every tick. Symptom = a wall of identical REJECT_GATEs (same medRet/pos/Sharpe), never a real candidate dir.

**The real path:** the two-step orchestrator (`runner/_orchestrator_helpers.py`): `prepare_round(n)` dumps prompts to /tmp → the AGENT reads each prompt and calls `sessions_spawn` itself (real LLM) → `finalize_round()` evaluates + writes the report.

**v2 fix that works (reusable pattern):** have the cron's own isolated agent turn GENERATE the candidate INLINE in a single turn, then finalize in that same turn. Do NOT use spawn+`sessions_yield` from a cron — v1 did and it ORPHANED candidates (the cron turn ends at the yield, `finalize_round` never runs, /tmp output left un-evaluated). Atomic inline-gen-then-finalize avoids the orphan.

**Leak guard:** an earlier inline-gen window leaked full `strategy.py` to Discord via the announce fallback (delivered=true). Keep `delivery.mode=none` on these silent rounds so generated code never hits the channel. Fix was prompt-only — no runner/protected file changed; the "no spawn" line in the old prompt was tick-cron boilerplate, not a deliberate guardrail.

